Combining single- and repeated-visit occupancy models to make the best of monitoring surveys: Appendix

2019-10-28

Authors Valentin Lauret, Hlne Labach, Matthieu Authier, Olivier Gimenez

In this Appendix, we present how we built a hybrid multi-method occupancy model analysing the aerial surveys with repeated-visit occupancy models, and the at-sea surveys with single-visit (SV) occupancy models.

Standard occupancy

Each detection y[i,j] at site i and visit j is taken in a Bernoulli distribution with parameter mu[i,j].

y[i,j]~dbern(mu[i,j])

The mu parameter is defined as mu[i,j] = p[i,j] * z[i,j].
p[i,j] is the probability of detecting the species at site i, during visit j.

The latent ecological state, i.e.the occupancy status, of site i is taken in a Bernoulli distribution of parameter psi

z[i]~dbern(psi[i]).

Then psi represent the occupancy probability of site i.

psi is modelled as a logistic regressions of the environmental covariates: bathymetry and SST.p is modeled as a logistic regression of sampling effort. alpha.psi, alpha.p, beta.sst, beta.bathy, and beta.eff are unknown parameters:

logit(psi[i]) = alpha.psi + beta.sst * SST[i] + beta.bathy * BATHY[i]

logit(p[i,j]) = alpha.p + beta.eff * EFF[i,j]

SST, BATHY, and EFF are the dataframes that contain the numerical values of respectively SST, bathymetry, and sampling effort.

Hybrid modelling

In the hybrid multi-method model, there are 2 different detection processes.

We separated a aerial detection matrix y_samm (with 4 columns as repeated visit at sites), from the at-sea detection matrix with a single visit y_gdegem, i.e.1 column.

There are 2 trials with Bernoulli distributions, with their associated p.

  • y_samm[i,j]~dbern(mu_samm[i,j]) , with mu_samm[i,j] = z[i] * p_samm[i,j]
  • y_gdegem[i]~dbern(mu_gdegem[i]), with mu_gdegem[i] = z[i] * p_gdegem[i]
    With logit(p_gdegem[i]) = alpha.p_gdegem + beta.eff.gd*eff.gd[i]

and logit(p_samm[i,j]) = alpha.p_samm + beta.eff.samm * eff.samm[i,j] + beta.occ2 * equals(j,2) + beta.occ3 * equals(j,3) + beta.occ4 * equals(j,4)

Hereafter, you would find the JAGS formulation of this occupancy model.

# Specify model in BUGS language
sink("mixed_std_sv.jags")
cat("
    model {
    
   # priors

    alpha.psi ~ dnorm(0,0.444) # occupancy intercept
    alpha.p_samm ~ dnorm(0,0.444) # detection samm intercept 
    alpha.p_gdegem ~ dnorm(0,0.444) # detection gdegem intercept 
    
    beta.sst ~ dnorm(0,0.444) # slope sst effect
    beta.bathy ~ dnorm(0,0.444) # slope bathy effect
    beta.eff.samm ~ dnorm(0,0.444)  # slope SAMM survey effort effect
    beta.eff.gd ~ dnorm(0,0.444)    # slope GDEGeM survey effort effect
    beta.occ2 ~ dnorm(0,0.444) # occasion effect
    beta.occ3 ~ dnorm(0,0.444) # occasion effect
    beta.occ4 ~ dnorm(0,0.444) # occasion effect    
    
    # Ecological submodel: Define state conditional on parameters
    
    ### initialisation: on met a chaque site la valeur 0 ou 1 selon la loi de bernouilli pour l'annee 1
    
   for (i in 1:nsite){
      z[i] ~ dbern(psi[i])
  
     logit(psi[i]) <- lpsi[i]
    
     lpsi[i] <- alpha.psi + beta.sst * SST[i] + beta.bathy * BATHY[i]
 
  }  # i  
    
     ### Observation model
  
    for(i in 1:nsite){
    ###p.gdegem

     mu.p_gdegem[i] <- z[i] * p_gdegem[i]

    logit(p_gdegem[i]) <- alpha.p_gdegem + beta.eff.gd*eff.gd[i]

   y_gdegem[i] ~ dbern(mu.p_gdegem[i])

    } #i 
    
for(i in 1:nsite){
   for (j in 1:nrep){

    mu.p_samm[i,j] <- z[i] * p_samm[i,j] 

    logit(p_samm[i,j]) <- lp_samm[i,j] 

    lp_samm[i,j] <- alpha.p_samm + beta.eff.samm * eff.samm[i,j] + beta.occ2 * equals(j,2) + beta.occ3 * equals(j,3) + beta.occ4 * equals(j,4) 
    
    y_samm[i,j] ~ dbern(mu.p_samm[i,j])
    
    
    } #j
    
  } #i
    
    }#fin du modele
    ", fill = TRUE)

sink()

Results

Hereafter, we show the effect size the environmental covariates on the estimated occupancy probability (psi).

Figure 1: Effect size of sea surface temperature (SST) and bathymetry on the proportion of area occupied by Bottlenose dolphins (Tursiops truncatus) obtained with the 2 monitoring programs. The a posteriori mean is given with the associated 95% credible interval. SV refers to single-visit occupancy models. RV refers to repeated-visit occupancy models. MM stands for multi-methods occupancy models, in which aerial surveys and at-sea surveys are combined. Hybrid refers to the model described above in this appendix. Estimates are given on the logit scale.

Now, we look at the map of the probability of occupancy. From the posterior mean of each occupancy models parameters, we generated the probability that site i is used by bottlenose dolphins:

\[ logit(\psi_{i}) = Intercept + \beta_{bathymetry}bathymetry_{i} + \beta_{SST}SST_{i}\]

Map of projected Psi for other models

Figure 2: Map of projected Psi for the Hybrid model

The hybrid model displayed similar estimates of effect size. We considered that the Hybrid model had a better performance than the multi-method SV model. The precision of the covariate effect size on psi was higher than MM SV on (Figure 1), but lower than MM STD.

This hybrid model highlights the flexibility of occupancy model to better fit with the sampling designs of non-standardized datasets. However, the separated formulation of the detection process into 2 matrices is relevant only if the monitoring programs are independant. Dependance between monitoring devies requires to model explicitly the covariation between detection probabilities (Clare et al.2017)

References

Clare J, McKinney ST, DePue JE, Loftin CS. 2017. Pairing field methods to improve inference in wildlife surveys while accommodating detection covariance. Ecological Applications 27:20312047.
